        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>- Choice of observing band -
We propose to use Band~7 because it is the ALMA band which provides best sensitivity in continuum from dust (at a given integration time). In principle in Band~9 (and 8) the dust emission would be brighter. Nevertheless, the atmospheric
conditions at that frequency would imply much longer integration times (a factor of 3 to reach the same dust mass sensitivity for a point source). 

- Correlator setup - 
We propose to use the correlator setup that offers broad continuum bandwidth (1.875~GHz) and channel spacing of 0.488~MHz. This mode offers the best continuum sensitivity and has enough velocity resolution (0.8~km/s after Hanning smoothing) 
to serendipitously search for molecular line emission in the 12CO(3-2) and 13CO(3-2). These lines will likely be detected in the disk around the primary 2M1207A and the study of the gas kinematics will be an important bonus of our program. We will use 4 spectral windows and dual polarization to maximize sensitivity.

- Imaging requirements -
 To separate the emission of the circumplanetary disk from the 
disk around the primary star we require high angular resolution (angular separation between the companions is 0.7''). We thus propose to use the configuration C34-5, which offers an angular resolution of about 0.3'' in Band 7 using uniform weighting to maximize sensitivity. The simulation described in the last section of the Scientific Justification shows that the proposed observations are adequate in terms of angular resolution, dynamic range, image fidelity (Fig. 3).

- Sensitivity - 
In order to get to the rms-noise level requested in the last section, i.e. about 0.02 mJy/beam at 0.87~mm, we request about 2.05 hours of on-source time, or 4.9 hours total (using the ALMA OT). Compared with our recent SCUBA2 observations of this system, the proposed ALMA observations are more sensitive by a factor of 100 at about the same wavelength.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
